---
import Text from "@/components/fundations/typography/Text.astro";
import Kicker from "@/components/fundations/typography/Kicker.astro";
const menuItems = [
  { label: "Latest Articles", href: "#_" },
  { label: "Popular Posts", href: "#_" },
  { label: "Categories", href: "#_" },
  { label: "Archives", href: "#_" },
  { label: "About the Author", href: "#_" },
  { label: "Subscribe to Newsletter", href: "#_" },
];
---

<section class="bg-white dark:bg-zinc-900">
  <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-8 md:px-12 lg:px-32 py-24">
    <div class="max-w-2xl md:text-balance">
      <Kicker>
        <time datetime="2025-01-09">2025-01-09</time>
      </Kicker>
      <Text
        tag="h1"
        variant="displayLG"
        class="text-zinc-900 mt-4 dark:text-white font-semibold tracking-tight"
      >
        The art and science of responsive web design
      </Text>
      <Text
        tag="p"
        variant="textLG"
        class="mt-4 font-medium text-zinc-500 dark:text-zinc-400 lg:text-balance"
      >
        Explore advanced strategies and practical insights for crafting
        responsive websites that adapt beautifully to every device and deliver
        exceptional user experiences.
      </Text>
      <div class="flex flex-shrink-0 mt-6 group">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-2">
          <div>
            <img
              class="inline-block rounded-full size-9"
              src="/avatars/1.jpg"
              alt=""
            />
          </div>
          <div>
            <Kicker> Michael Andreuzza </Kicker>
            <Text
              tag="p"
              variant="textXS"
              class="font-medium text-zinc-400 dark:text-zinc-500"
            >
              @Mike_Andreuzza
            </Text>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div
      class="relative pt-12 mt-12 border-t border-zinc-200 dark:border-zinc-800 grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-3 gap-12"
    >
      <aside class="hidden lg:block">
        <Kicker> Table of contents </Kicker>
        <ul class="mt-4 pt-4 border-t border-zinc-200 dark:border-zinc-800">
          {
            menuItems.map((item) => (
              <li>
                <a
                  href="#_"
                  class="font-medium text-zinc-900 dark:text-white  hover:text-blue-600 dark:hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
                >
                  {item.label}
                </a>
              </li>
            ))
          }
        </ul>
      </aside>
      <div
        class="mx-auto prose text-zinc-500 dark:text-zinc-400 prose-a:font-semibold prose-a:text-blue-300 dark:prose-a:text-blue-400 hover:prose-a:text-zinc-900 dark:hover:prose-a:text-white prose-headings:text-zinc-900 dark:prose-headings:text-white prose-blockquote:text-blue-400 dark:prose-blockquote:text-blue-300 prose-code:text-blue-400 dark:prose-code:text-blue-300 prose-strong:text-blue-500 dark:prose-strong:text-blue-400 prose-img:rounded-3xl prose-pre:rounded-2xl lg:col-span-2"
      >
        <p>
          In a world where users expect instant access and flawless experiences,
          responsive web design is the backbone of modern digital products. Your
          site must do more than just fit the screen—it should feel natural and
          intuitive, no matter the device. Responsive design is about
          flexibility, but also about anticipating user needs and delivering
          content in the most effective way possible.
        </p>
        <h2>Start Small, Grow Smart: Mobile-First</h2>
        <p>
          Building with a mobile-first mindset means you begin with the
          essentials: clear content, fast performance, and easy navigation. As
          you scale up to tablets and desktops, you layer on enhancements that
          take advantage of larger screens. This approach not only guarantees
          accessibility for mobile users, but also creates a strong foundation
          for every device.
        </p>
        <h3>Benefits of Prioritizing Mobile</h3>
        <p>
          By focusing on mobile first, you’re forced to distill your message and
          features to what matters most. This leads to cleaner layouts, faster
          load times, and a more focused user experience. It also means your
          site is ready for the next wave of devices—whatever shape or size they
          may be.
        </p>
        <blockquote>
          <p>“Responsive web design is not a feature, it’s a must.”</p>
          <small>- Jeffrey Zeldman</small>
        </blockquote>
        <h2>Design for Everyone: Accessibility & Inclusion</h2>
        <p>
          True responsive design goes beyond breakpoints and grids. It’s about
          making your site usable for everyone, including people with
          disabilities. Use semantic HTML, provide alt text for images, and
          ensure your color choices meet accessibility standards. The more
          inclusive your design, the more people you’ll reach—and the more
          impact your work will have.
        </p>
        <h2>Performance: The Unsung Hero</h2>
        <p>
          Don’t let beautiful design slow you down. Optimize images, minimize
          code, and test your site on real devices. Fast, responsive sites keep
          users engaged and boost your SEO, making performance a key part of
          your responsive strategy.
        </p>
        <h2>Final Thoughts</h2>
        <p>
          Responsive web design is a journey, not a destination. By embracing
          mobile-first principles, prioritizing accessibility, and never losing
          sight of performance, you’ll create digital experiences that stand the
          test of time—and delight users everywhere.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
